output.text: Here is what I can do:
A booking fee is a non-refundable fee charged on some mortgages to secure a particular mortgage deal.
A broker is a person who buys and sells goods or assets on behalf of others in exchange for commission on completion of the deal.
A buildings survey or valuation report is commissioned by the buyer. It provides an independent view of the property's value, construction and condition.
A cashback mortgage is when mortgage lenders give borrowers a one off lump sum payment at the start of the mortgage as an incentive for choosing them.
A completion fee is a charge which covers the cost of electronically transferring the mortgage funds to the borrower.
A contingency fund or budget is the amount of money set aside to cover the cost of unexpected expenses.

A decision in principle or DIP is a quick decision that tells you the amount you may be able to borrow based on information you provide and our security checks, including a soft credit check (which will not affect your credit rating).
A deposit is the amount of money paid as a first installment towards the value of your property. The remainder will dictate the size of your mortgage.
A discounted rate mortgage is when the mortgage interest rate is discounted from the ANZ Variable Rate. When the discount period ends, the mortgage interest rate reverts to the ANZ Variable Rate.

A fixed rate mortgage means the interest rate you pay on your mortgage will not change until an agreed date, no matter what happens to interest rates. This means your repayment amount will stay the same each month until the agreed date.
A green deal is a government scheme that could help you make energy-saving improvements to your home and find the best way to pay for them.
A higher lending charge or HLC is a fee lenders may apply to borrowing over a certain percentage of a property value.
A key facts illustrator is a document that all lenders are requied to provide by law. It sets out the details of all associated rates and fees for a mortgage.

All mortgage applicants will need to supply proof of identity, proof of income, proof of address, 3 months worth of bank statements, details of other income, details of protection plans and employer benefits and details of all current non-mortgage borrowing. Please note depending on your mortgage type or individual circumstances additional information may be required.
A mortgage deed is a legal document drawn up by the lender which formally secures the money you borrow against the property.
A mortgage is a loan taken out to buy property or land. Most run for 25 years but the term can be shorter or longer.
An arrangement fee is a fee charged for the administration involved in arranging the loan.

An Early Repayment Charge (ERC) is a charge you may have to pay if you repay the whole or part of your mortgage, by paying it back early (which includes if you move to a different product or move to a different lender) during a certain period. Early repayment charges do not apply to tracker mortgages
An endowment mortgage is a mortgage linked to an endowment insurance policy which is intended to repay the capital sum on maturity
An equity release scheme is a way of extracting cash out of your property by taking out a loan secured on your home.
An exit fee is a fee payable to lenders when you fully repay your mortgage. ANZ does not charge an exit fee.
An extended tie in period is when a borrower has to keep their mortgage with the lender for a set period of time after a fixed rate mortgage period has ended.
An interest only mortgage means the monthly payment covers just the interest and doesn't pay off the capital borrowed.
An intermediary is a firm or an individual (such as a broker) who acts as a mediator between parties in the home buying process.

An offset mortgage is when you link your mortgage to a savings account, the contents of which 'offset' against the balance of your mortgage.  This means you don't pay interest on the balance of your account.

A property chain is sequence of linked purchases with those that are buying or selling their properties to each other at the same time, each of which is usually dependent on the buying and selling of the other properties in the chain.
APR or APRC stands for the Annual Percentage Rate of Charge used to compare loan offers.
A repayment mortgage means that over the mortgage period your monthy payments will be made up of capital and interest, and will repay the loan.
A sealed bid is when multiple buyers are invited to submit their offers in confidence by a specific date as part of the buying process.
A service fee is the fee charged by a lender who, with the customer's written consent, requests details from their existing mortgage lender.
A standard valuation report determines the market value of the property they wish to borrow against.
A tracker mortgage tracks the Bank of England base rate, where as the lender (ANZ in this case) sets the rate for a variable rate mortgage.
A tracker mortgage tracks the Bank of England base rate, where as the lender sets the rate for a variable rate mortgage.
A tracker rate mortgage means the interest rate payable on your loan will rise and fall in line with changes to the Bank of England base rate. This means your monthly repayment may vary.
A variable rate mortgage means the interest rate payable on your loan may rise and fall in line with changes to the interest rate as decided by the lender. This means your monthly repayment may vary.
Buildings insurance can cover the cost of rebuilding or repairing your property if it is damaged or destroyed and is often a requirement of your mortgage lender.
Capped rate mortgages are a type of variable rate mortgage. They have an interest rate ceiling meaning your payments won't exceed a certain amount.
CCJ stands for county court judgement.  This is a court order which states that you must pay money you owe to a debt.
Collars apply to some variable rate mortgages.  The collar is the minimum rate of interest that can be charged by the lender over a fixed period.

Conveyancers have the same role as solicitors who specialise in property. The main difference is that they are only qualified to deal with property law. Conveyancers often cost less than solicitors, as they are only trained in this area.
Conveyancing is the preparation of legal documents for the transfer of a property from one owner to another.
Equity is the difference between a property's actual value and the mortgage held against it.
Estate agents market properties to potential buyers and negotiate with them on behalf of the sellers. Their role also involves valuing properties and comparing them to others on the market.
Fee saver is a product with no booking or completion fee.

Fixed rate mortgages offer a set rate over a given term meaning your monthly repayments remain the same each month, whereas a variable rate can change meaning your monthly repayments could go up or down during the term.
Gazanging occurs when a seller gets cold feet after accepting an offer by remaining in their property and leaving the buyer hanging.

Gazumping occurs when a seller agrees to accept an offer from one buyer, but then goes on to accept a higher offer from someone else. The first buyers are 'Gazumped' and can lose the property they planned to buy.
Gazundering occurs when the buyer reduces their offer at the last minute, often just before contracts are exchanged.
If you buy a freehold property, it means you own the building and the land it is situated on, and you will have the right to live there for as long as you like.
If you buy a freehold property, it means you own the building and the land it is situated on, and you will have the right to live there for as long as you like.

If you buy a leasehold property  common if you are buying a flat in a shared building  you are actually buying the rights to live in a property for a set period of time. Unlike a freehold, you won't actually own the property or the land it's built on.
In a joint mortgage, the mortgage is taken out by more than one person. They are each liable for the mortgage repayments and have equal rights to the property
Interest is a charge for borrowing money.
In the UK you're never far away from a ANZ branch. Simply enter your postcode, location or sort-code into our map http://bit.ly/2ftUpB8

Its is a one-off tax payment that you have to pay if you buy a property above a certain threshold.

Leasehold is ownership of a property, but not the land on which it stands whereas freehold is ownership of both the land and the property.
Loan to Value (LTV) compares how much you wish to borrow in relation to how much the property is worth (loan-to-value).
Mortgage lenders provide the financing to buy a home. You can get a mortgage  a homebuyer's loan  direct from banks, building societies or specialist mortgage lenders
Mortgage payment protection insurance or MPPI is designed to cover your mortgage repayments if you're unable to work.
Negative equity is when the value of a propertyis lower than the mortgage held against it.
Payment protection insurance or PPI is an insurance deigned to cover the cost of loan repayments should you be unable to work.
Portability is the ease with which you can move your mortgage from one property to another.
Repayment vehicles are assets such as savings or investments designed to cover the capital cost at the end of an interest only mortgage.
Right to Buy is a government scheme enabling eligible council and housing association tenants in England to buy their home
Right to buy is a scheme designed to help council property tennants buy their property whereas help to buy is a scheme to help first time buyers with a higher loan to value.
Service charges are fees that most leaseholders pay to cover their share of the cost of maintaining the building they live in.
Shared ownership is when someone buys a proportion of the property they live in and pays rent on the remainder, typically to a local authority or housing association.

Solicitors are qualified to practise in any area of law but some may choose to become property specialists. They will check the contract and any legal documents associated with transferring a property from one owner to another
SVR stands for Standard Variable Rate.  This means the interest rate you pay is subject to change and is determined by the lender.
The Bank of England Base Rate is set by the Bank of England. ANZ Tracker mortgage interest rates are linked with a margin above this Base Rate

The estimated property value is the purchase price or the conservative market value of the property being used as security. Your mortgage lender needs to know this because the money you borrow will be secured against the value of your property.
The Help to Buy mortgage guarantee scheme enables participating lenders to provide higher loan to value (LTV) mortgages to first time buyers. ANZ have joined the scheme.
The interest rate is the percentage rate at which the lender calculates the interest they charge the borrower for the mortgage.
The Land Registry registers the ownership of property and land in England and Wales.person. They are each liable for the mortgage repayments and have equal rights to the property
The monthly repayment is the amount you repay to your mortgage lender each month.
The mortgage term is the length of time over which a mortgage is taken.
The rebuild cost is the amount it would cost to completely rebuild your home if it was destroyed beyond repair.
